Yes — a Durable Object can wake itself up and run with no external connections at all, but not with a plain `setInterval` loop. The mechanism for this is the **Alarms API**.

## Why a naive loop doesn't work

A DO only stays alive while there's activity. After all requests/events finish, it idles and then hibernates or gets evicted (inactivity timeout is roughly 70–140 seconds with no incoming requests or open WebSockets). A `setInterval` callback keeps it from *hibernating*, but it doesn't protect you from eviction on runtime restarts or code deploys — and when eviction happens, your in-memory timer is simply gone forever. Nothing will ever recreate it.

## What actually works: chained alarms

`ctx.storage.setAlarm(timestamp)` is persisted in the DO's durable storage. When the alarm fires, the runtime wakes the object (running the constructor again if it was hibernated) and calls your `alarm()` handler — no request, RPC, or WebSocket needed. Alarms survive eviction, hibernation, and deploys, and have at-least-once delivery with retries. They don't repeat automatically, so you re-arm at the end of each run:

```ts
import { DurableObject } from "cloudflare:workers";

export class Poller extends DurableObject {
  // Call this once (via fetch/RPC) to kick off the loop
  async start() {
    await this.ctx.storage.put("running", true);
    // Only set if one isn't already scheduled, so start() is idempotent
    if ((await this.ctx.storage.getAlarm()) === null) {
      await this.ctx.storage.setAlarm(Date.now() + 20_000);
    }
  }

  async stop() {
    await this.ctx.storage.put("running", false);
    await this.ctx.storage.deleteAlarm();
  }

  async alarm() {
    if (!(await this.ctx.storage.get("running"))) return;

    // Re-arm FIRST so a failure in the API call doesn't kill the loop
    await this.ctx.storage.setAlarm(Date.now() + 20_000);

    const res = await fetch("https://api.example.com/poll");
    await this.ctx.storage.put("lastResult", await res.json());
  }
}
```

Two caveats:

- **You need one external call to bootstrap it.** A DO instance doesn't exist until something addresses it, so a Worker request (or a cron-triggered Worker) has to call `start()` once. After that it's fully self-driving.
- **Cost.** Every 20-second wake is a billed invocation plus duration — that's ~4,300 invocations/day per object. Fine for one or a handful of pollers; Cloudflare's own guidance warns against putting short-interval alarms on *many* objects. If you have exactly one global poll and don't need per-entity state, a [Cron Trigger](https://developers.cloudflare.com/workers/configuration/cron-triggers/) on a plain Worker is simpler — but its minimum granularity is 1 minute, so for every-20-seconds the DO alarm chain is the right tool.

Also make the handler idempotent (check state before acting), since alarms can occasionally fire more than once.

So the answer is yes, you can keep a Durable Object alive using alarms—specifically by chaining them every 20 seconds. The key distinction is that while `setInterval` prevents hibernation, it doesn't protect against eviction after the inactivity timeout of 70-140 seconds with no incoming requests. Alarms work differently because they can wake the DO even without external connections, making them the reliable approach here.

One important caveat: alarms persist across evictions and restarts with guaranteed at-least-once delivery and retries, but you need to bootstrap the system by calling the DO once to set that initial alarm. There's also a cost consideration—waking every 20 seconds incurs invocation charges, and the docs caution against very short intervals across many objects, though it's fine for a single or handful of DOs. For work that's sub-second or purely in-memory while the DO is active, you can combine both approaches.

This app already has the *state* half of persistence solved — let me untangle the two meanings of "persist" for a DO, because they're different mechanisms.

## 1. State persistence: you already have it

Your `MyDurableObject` is SQLite-backed (declared via `new_sqlite_classes = ["MyDurableObject"]` in `wrangler.toml`), and both methods write to durable storage:

```12:14:apps/durable-objects/src/counter.ts
    this.ctx.storage.sql.exec(
      "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS counter (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, value INTEGER NOT NULL)",
    );
```

Anything in `ctx.storage.sql` or `ctx.storage.put()` survives hibernation, eviction, deploys, and machine moves — forever, until you delete it. The counter value will still be there if the object isn't touched for a year. Note the constructor pattern here is exactly right for this: `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS` re-runs on every wake-up, so the object rebuilds its runtime context from durable state each time. That's the core DO discipline — treat instance fields as a disposable cache, storage as the truth.

## 2. Liveness persistence: the object does *not* stay running

Right now `MyDurableObject` only executes when a request arrives at the Worker's `fetch` handler. Between calls it hibernates (~10s after going idle) and is eventually evicted — that's expected and free. If what you want is the DO to keep *doing things* with no incoming requests (like the every-20s loop we discussed), you add an alarm chain. Applied to this class:

```ts
export class MyDurableObject extends DurableObject<Env> {
  constructor(ctx: DurableObjectState, env: Env) {
    super(ctx, env);
    this.ctx.storage.sql.exec(
      "CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS counter (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, value INTEGER NOT NULL)",
    );
  }

  // Call once via a stub to make the object self-sustaining
  async startHeartbeat(): Promise<void> {
    await this.ctx.storage.put("heartbeat", true);
    if ((await this.ctx.storage.getAlarm()) === null) {
      await this.ctx.storage.setAlarm(Date.now() + 20_000);
    }
  }

  async stopHeartbeat(): Promise<void> {
    await this.ctx.storage.put("heartbeat", false);
    await this.ctx.storage.deleteAlarm();
  }

  async alarm(): Promise<void> {
    if (!(await this.ctx.storage.get<boolean>("heartbeat"))) return;

    // Re-arm first so a thrown error below can't break the chain
    await this.ctx.storage.setAlarm(Date.now() + 20_000);

    this.ctx.storage.sql.exec(
      `INSERT INTO counter (id, value) VALUES (2, 1)
       ON CONFLICT(id) DO UPDATE SET value = value + 1`,
    );
    // ...or your external API call here
  }
}
```

And a route in `index.ts` to bootstrap it:

```ts
if (url.pathname === "/start") {
  await stub.startHeartbeat();
  return new Response("heartbeat started");
}
```

The alarm timestamp itself lives in durable storage, so the wake-up chain survives eviction and deploys just like your counter rows do. Between firings the object hibernates and costs nothing in duration; each firing bills one request (a `setAlarm` also counts as one row write under the SQLite billing that went live in January).

One thing to know for local dev: `wrangler dev` persists both SQLite state and pending alarms to disk, so you can kill the process, restart, and watch the chain resume — a nice way to convince yourself the persistence actually works.

If you meant a third thing — keeping the object *pinned in memory* to preserve instance fields — that's the one you can't have. `keepAlive`-style heartbeats (what the Agents SDK does) only reduce eviction frequency during active work; the platform's contract is that memory is always disposable and storage is always durable.

The user is asking how to keep a Durable Object alive and persistent—they likely mean how to make it stay running continuously rather than just storing state. Since their app already uses SQLite for persistence, I should show them how to add an alarm loop to their Durable Object to keep it self-sustaining and running.
